(5) The Aediles—The aediles were four in number, tw064 curule and two plebeian. Notwithstanding this distinction they were all elected in the comitia tributa and were practically of the same rank, differing but little in their dutieS. (a) They were the superintendents of the marketS, and had tribunals in the forum from which they decided petty disputes between buyers and sellers. (b) They superintended the distribution of the grain furnished by the state at a low cost to the needy commonS. (c) They had general police dutieS, including65 oversight of public order, the water supply, streets and squareS, and precautions against fire. (d) They had the management of certain public gameS. This last function made the office eagerly sought, for the commons took great delight in the showS, and the aedile who gratified them with expensive games would reap his reward when he ran for another office.
